In computational modeling and time-series data, temporal resolution refers to the specific time intervals or steps at which data is sampled.
High Temporal Resolution: Sampling data every few seconds, minutes, or hours (e.g., real-time stock market data or IoT sensor logs).
Low Temporal Resolution: Sampling data on a weekly, monthly, or yearly basis (e.g., annual climate trends or quarterly financial reports).
Why it Matters: The Trade-OffIn almost every technological or scientific field, there is an inherent trade-off between temporal resolution and 
spatial or spectral resolution. Acquiring highly detailed pictures or deep, granular data takes more time, meaning you often have to sacrifice 
how frequently you can take the measurement.
